2. Goal of the Test

The goal was to run a pretrained YOLOv7 model on either:

• sample images
• a webcam feed

The standard command used to run detection on images is:

python detect.py --weights yolov7.pt --source inference/images

For webcam detection the command is:

python detect.py --weights yolov7.pt --source 0

Explanation of parameters:

--weights yolov7.pt
This loads the trained YOLOv7 model file.

--source inference/images
This runs detection on sample images included in the repository.

--source 0
This tells YOLOv7 to use the laptop webcam.

3. Issue Encountered

While attempting to run the command above, an error occurred when the model attempted to load the .pt checkpoint file.

The error originated from the model loading function inside the repository.

The failing code was located in the file:

models/experimental.py

The original line of code was:

ckpt = torch.load(w, map_location=map_location)  # load

This caused an error when attempting to load the YOLOv7 model.

4. Root Cause

The issue was caused by changes in newer versions of PyTorch (version 2.x).

Recent versions of PyTorch introduced stricter security rules for loading serialized model checkpoints.

By default, PyTorch now tries to load weights-only checkpoints, which prevents full model objects from being loaded unless explicitly allowed.

However, YOLOv7 checkpoints contain the entire model object, not just the weights.

Because of this mismatch, the default loading behavior caused the model loading process to fail.

5. Solution

The issue was resolved by modifying the checkpoint loading command inside the YOLOv7 repository.

The file edited was:

models/experimental.py

Original code:

ckpt = torch.load(w, map_location=map_location)  # load

Modified code:

ckpt = torch.load(w, map_location=map_location, weights_only=False)  # load

Adding the weights_only=False argument tells PyTorch to allow loading the full checkpoint object instead of forcing a weights-only load.

6. Result

After modifying the code, the YOLOv7 model successfully loaded.

The detection command was then able to run correctly.

Example command used:

python detect.py --weights yolov7.pt --source 0

This connects the model to the laptop webcam and runs real-time object detection.

The program then displays bounding boxes around detected objects.
